<text xml:lang="ta">
  <body>
    <div xml:id="PN381">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>ūṉu mūṇu muṉaiyi ṉiṉiteṉap</l>
<l>pāliṟ peytavum pākiṟ koṇṭavum</l>
<l>maḷavupu kalantu mellitu paruki</l>
<l>viruntuṟut tāṟṟi yiruntaṉe mākac</l>
<l>ceṉmō perumavem viḻavuṭai nāṭṭeṉa</l>
<l>yāntaṉ ṉaṟiyuna mākat tāṉperi</l>
<l>taṉpuṭai maiyi ṉempiri vañcit</l>
<l>tuṇariyatu koḷāa vākip paḻamūḻttup</l>
<l>payampakar vaṟiyā mayaṅkariṉ mutupāḻp</l>
<l>peyalpey taṉṉa celvat tāṅka</l>
<l>ṇīyā maṉṉar puṟaṅkaṭait tōṉṟic</l>
<l>citāar vaḷpiṟ citarppuṟan taṭāri</l>
<l>yūṉcukir valanta teṇka ṇoṟṟi</l>
<l>viralvicai tavirkku maralaiyil pāṇiyi</l>
<l>ṉilampā ṭakaṟṟal yāvatu pulampoṭu</l>
<l>terumara luyakkamun tīrkkuve mataṉā</l>
<l>lirunilaṅ kūlam pāṟak kōṭai</l>
<l>varumaḻai muḻakkicaik kōṭiya piṉṟaic</l>
<l>cēyai yāyiṉu mivaṇai yāyiṉu</l>
<l>mitaṟkoṇ ṭaṟinai vāḻiyō kiṇaiva</l>
<l>ciṟunaṉi, yoruvaḻip paṭarkeṉ ṟōṉē yentai</l>
<l>yoliveḷ ḷaruvi vēṅkaṭa nāṭa</l>
<l>ṉuṟuvaruñ ciṟuvaru mūḻmā ṟuykku</l>
<l>maṟattuṟai yampiyiṉ māṉa maṟappiṉ</l>
<l>ṟiruṅkō ḷīrāp pūṭkaik</l>
<l>karumpa ṉūraṉ kātal makaṉē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Since he feared separation from us because of possessing</l>
<l>love that is great [for] us, while we knew him, (6f.)</l>
<l>[he] said: “go, great man to our land that as festivals, (5) </l>
<l>drinking softly after having measured [and] mixed (3)</l>
<l>pourings of milk and takings of sugar syrup, (2)</l>
<l>thinking [it] sweet when disinclined for [more] meat and food,” (1)</l>
<l>[and] in that place of wealth that is like rain raining, (10)</l>
<l>in an old [place of] ruin with entangled thickets that did not know of announcing yield (9)</l>
<l>after the fruit rotted, being one that is not taken [although there] in clusters, (8)</l>
<l>after having appeared at the outer gate of kings who do not give (11) </l>
<l>we have [now] ended [our] scorching affliction (16a-c)</l>
<l>along with any loneliness by dispelling poverty (15)</l>
<l>with the flawless beat that regulated the speed of [our] fingers (14)</l>
<l>when pressing the clear eye encircled by meat(?) fibres (13)  </l>
<l>of [our] Taṭāri drum whose back scatters ragged straps (12).</l>
<l>	Therefore, (16d)</l>
<l>after the west wind has run to the thunder sound </l>
<l>of the coming rain to scatter grains on the vast ground (17f.)</l>
<l>if you be far of if you be near, (19)</l>
<l>take this in [and] know, may you live, o Kiṇai drummer: (20)</l>
<l>he who said may you set out on one way, a little, much(?), is our father (21)</l>
<l>man from the land of the Vēṅkaṭa mountain with sounding white waterfalls, (22)</l>
<l>the beloved son of the may from the town of Karumpaṉ (26)</l>
</lg>
